%U A394371 620160978500033613594746519224542615249600,978680714088698825382169269787209410778375430200,1568570402130127325904031027296283623494442944222692800
%N A394371 a(n) = (16*n)!/((2*n)!*(4*n)!*(10*n)!).
%F A394371 O.g.f.: hypergeom([1/16, 1/8, 3/16, 5/16, 3/8, 7/16, 9/16, 5/8, 11/16, 13/16, 7/8, 15/16], [1/10, 1/5, 3/10, 2/5, 1/2, 1/2, 3/5, 7/10, 4/5, 9/10, 1],(2^44)*x/(5^10) ).
%F A394371 E.g.f.: hypergeom([1/16, 1/8, 3/16, 5/16, 3/8, 7/16, 9/16, 5/8, 11/16, 13/16, 7/8, 15/16], [1/10, 1/5, 3/10, 2/5, 1/2, 1/2, 3/5, 7/10, 4/5, 9/10, 1,1],(2^44)*x/(5^10)).
%F A394371   a(n) = Integral_{x=0..(2^44)/(5^10)} x^n*W(x), where W(x) = (5^9*sqrt(5)/((2^45)*Pi))*MeijerG([[],[0,0,-1/2,-1/2,-1/10,-1/5,-3/10,-2/5,-3/5,-7/10,-4/5,-9/10]],[[-1/16,-1/8,-3/16,-5/16,-3/8,-7/16,-9/16,-5/8,-11/16,-13/16,-7/8,-15/16],[]],x/((2^44)/(5^10)) ), where MeijerG is the Meijer G-function (here in Maple notation).
%F A394371 W(x) is a positive function on x=(0, (2^44)/(5^10)), it is singular at x = 0 and decreases monotonically to zero at x = (2^44)/(5^10). W(x) can be represented in terms of twelve generalized hypergeometric functions of type 12F11. This integral representation is unique, as W(x) is the solution of the Hausdorff power moment problem.
